According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', Stephen had no "wish to marry a lawful wife but took to himself [[concubine]]s and [[harlot]]s".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 154.109–110), p. 134.</ref>{{sfn|Kristó|Makk|1996|p=155}} However, his advisors, "grieving that the kingdom was in a sorry state and the King without a heir",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 154.110), p. 134.</ref> persuaded him to marry.{{sfn|Kristó|Makk|1996|p=155}} They chose a daughter of the late [[Robert I of Capua]] as their monarch's wife,{{sfn|Kristó|Makk|1996|p=155}} although her name was not recorded.{{sfn|Kristó|Makk|1996|p=Appendix 2}} Stephen died childless.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=50}}

